04251nam a22005415i 9780226116143DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015012981  a97802261161437 a10.7208/97802261161432doi  a(DE-B1597)568274  a(OCoLC)1233041092  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aQL644b.C73 2015 4aQL644b.C73 2015 7aNAT0000002bisacsh04a597.82231 aCrump, Marty, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEye of Newt and Toe of Frog, Adder's Fork and Lizard's Leg :bThe Lore and Mythology of Amphibians and Reptiles /cMarty Crump. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b155 color plates, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1 Talk to the Animals -- t2 In the Beginning -- t3 Snakes -- t4 Songs and Thunderbolts -- t5 A Second Chance -- t6 Of Love, Morals, and Death -- t7 The Lighter Side -- t8 Tailless Wonders, Naked Serpents, and Fire Lizards -- t9 Marshmallow-Eaters, Methuselahs, Spiny-Backs, Were-Lizards, and Protectors -- t10 Move Aside, Viagra -- t11 Pick Your Poison—Blood, Venom, Skin, or Bones -- t12 Like a Hell-Broth, Boil and Bubble -- t13 “How ’bout Them Toad Suckers” -- t14 Singing Tuatara from Their Holes -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrogs are worshipped for bringing nourishing rains, but blamed for devastating floods. Turtles are admired for their wisdom and longevity, but ridiculed for their sluggish and cowardly behavior. Snakes are respected for their ability to heal and restore life, but despised as symbols of evil. Lizards are revered as beneficent guardian spirits, but feared as the Devil himself. In this ode to toads and snakes, newts and tuatara, crocodiles and tortoises, herpetologist and science writer Marty Crump explores folklore across the world and throughout time. From creation myths to trickster tales; from associations with fertility and rebirth to fire and rain; and from the use of herps in folk medicines and magic, as food, pets, and gods, to their roles in literature, visual art, music, and dance, Crump reveals both our love and hatred of amphibians and reptiles—and their perceived power. In a world where we keep home terrariums at the same time that we battle invasive cane toads, and where public attitudes often dictate that the cute and cuddly receive conservation priority over the slimy and venomous, she shows how our complex and conflicting perceptions threaten the conservation of these ecologically vital animals. Sumptuously illustrated, Eye of Newt and Toe of Frog, Adder’s Fork and Lizard’s Leg is a beautiful and enthralling brew of natural history and folklore, sobering science and humor, that leaves us with one irrefutable lesson: love herps. Warts, scales, and all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAmphibiansxFolklore. 0aAmphibiansxMythology. 0aReptilesxFolklore. 0aReptilesxMythology. 7aNATURE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226116143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226116143.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles